' transatlantic literary studies seek to understand North American, British and Irish literature as linked with each other by virtue of multi-layered historical and cultural ties and pay special attention to the many refractions and mutual interferences that have characterized these traditions since colonial times. This handbook brings together articles that summarize some of the crucial transatlantic concepts, debates and topics. The contributions contained in this volume examine periods in literary and cultural history, literary movements, individual authors as well as genres from a transatlantic perspective, combining theoretical insight with textual analysis.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 16. Mai 2019) 0aCanadian literaturexHistory and criticism. 0aComparative literaturexAmerican and English. 0aComparative literaturexEnglish and American. 0aCultural fusion in literature. 0aIdentity (Philosophical concept) in literature. 0aTravelers' writingsxHistory and criticism. 4aAmerican Literature. 4aAnglophone Literature. 4aBritish Literature. 4aTransatlantic Literary Studies. 70(DE-601)1062450070(DE-588)4035965-7aLiteraturbeziehungen2gnd 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / American / General.2bisacsh1 aStraub, Julia, eeditor.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2016z9783110485103oZDB-23-DGG08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE Literary, Cultural and Area Studies 2016z9783110485264oZDB-23-DKU0 cEPUBz97831103934150 cprintz978311037637140uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9783110376739423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9783110376739.jpg  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_LT  aEBA_DGALL  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_LT  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA14ALL  aPDA1